## 🗺️ React Routing Architecture

Modern React apps are **Single Page Applications (SPAs)** — the server only sends ONE HTML file, and JavaScript handles navigation by rendering different components. React Router is the standard library for this.

---

## 1️⃣ What is Client-Side Routing?

Traditional websites request a new HTML page from the server on every navigation. SPAs instead:
1. Load a single HTML file once.
2. Use JavaScript to swap components without a page reload.
3. Update the URL bar using the History API.

This makes navigation feel instant.

---

## 2️⃣ Setup (React Router v6)

```bash
npm install react-router-dom
```

```javascript
// main.jsx
import { BrowserRouter } from 'react-router-dom'

ReactDOM.createRoot(document.getElementById('root')).render(
  <BrowserRouter>
    <App />
  </BrowserRouter>
)
```

---

## 3️⃣ Defining Routes

```javascript
// App.jsx
import { Routes, Route, Navigate } from 'react-router-dom'

function App() {
  return (
    <Routes>
      <Route path="/" element={<Home />} />
      <Route path="/about" element={<About />} />
      <Route path="/users/:id" element={<UserDetail />} />  {/* Dynamic segment */}
      <Route path="/dashboard/*" element={<Dashboard />} />  {/* Nested routes */}
      <Route path="*" element={<NotFound />} />  {/* 404 catch-all */}
      <Route path="/old-path" element={<Navigate to="/new-path" replace />} />
    </Routes>
  )
}
```

---

## 4️⃣ Navigation

```javascript
import { Link, NavLink, useNavigate } from 'react-router-dom'

// Link — prevents full page reload
<Link to="/about">About Us</Link>

// NavLink — adds 'active' class/style when route matches
<NavLink to="/about" className={({ isActive }) => isActive ? 'active' : ''}>
  About
</NavLink>

// Programmatic navigation
function LoginPage() {
  const navigate = useNavigate()

  const handleLogin = async () => {
    await loginUser()
    navigate('/dashboard', { replace: true })  // replace prevents back button to login
    navigate(-1)  // Go back one step
  }
}
```

---

## 5️⃣ URL Parameters & Query Strings

```javascript
// Route: /users/:id
function UserDetail() {
  const { id } = useParams()  // { id: "123" }
  return <h1>User #{id}</h1>
}

// URL: /search?q=react&page=2
function SearchPage() {
  const [searchParams, setSearchParams] = useSearchParams()
  const query = searchParams.get('q')   // "react"
  const page = searchParams.get('page') // "2"

  return (
    <>
      <p>Searching for: {query} (page {page})</p>
      <button onClick={() => setSearchParams({ q: query, page: '3' })}>
        Next Page
      </button>
    </>
  )
}
```

---

## 6️⃣ Nested Routes & Layout Routes

```javascript
// Layout route — renders shared UI (nav, sidebar) + child routes via <Outlet>
function DashboardLayout() {
  return (
    <div className="dashboard">
      <Sidebar />
      <main>
        <Outlet />  {/* Child routes render here */}
      </main>
    </div>
  )
}

function App() {
  return (
    <Routes>
      <Route path="/dashboard" element={<DashboardLayout />}>
        <Route index element={<Overview />} />          {/* /dashboard */}
        <Route path="courses" element={<Courses />} />  {/* /dashboard/courses */}
        <Route path="settings" element={<Settings />} />{/* /dashboard/settings */}
      </Route>
    </Routes>
  )
}
```

---

## 7️⃣ Protected Routes (Auth Guards)

```javascript
function ProtectedRoute({ children }) {
  const { user, loading } = useAuth()
  const location = useLocation()

  if (loading) return <LoadingSpinner />
  if (!user) return <Navigate to="/login" state={{ from: location }} replace />
  return children
}

// Usage
<Route path="/dashboard" element={
  <ProtectedRoute><Dashboard /></ProtectedRoute>
} />

// After login, redirect back to where they came from
function LoginPage() {
  const location = useLocation()
  const navigate = useNavigate()
  const from = location.state?.from?.pathname || '/dashboard'

  const handleLogin = async () => {
    await login()
    navigate(from, { replace: true })
  }
}
```

---

## 8️⃣ Location & State

```javascript
const location = useLocation()

// location.pathname  → "/dashboard/courses"
// location.search    → "?tab=active"
// location.hash      → "#section-1"
// location.state     → { from: "/login" }  (passed via navigate)

// Passing state via navigation
navigate('/confirm', { state: { orderData } })

// Receiving state
const { orderData } = useLocation().state || {}
```

---

## 9️⃣ Route-Level Code Splitting

Lazily load route components for faster initial load:

```javascript
import { lazy, Suspense } from 'react'

const Dashboard = lazy(() => import('./pages/Dashboard'))
const Settings = lazy(() => import('./pages/Settings'))

function App() {
  return (
    <Suspense fallback={<LoadingScreen />}>
      <Routes>
        <Route path="/dashboard" element={<Dashboard />} />
        <Route path="/settings" element={<Settings />} />
      </Routes>
    </Suspense>
  )
}
```

---

## 💡 Summary

| Concept | Code |
|---|---|
| Setup | `<BrowserRouter>` wraps app |
| Define routes | `<Routes><Route path="" element={}/></Routes>` |
| Navigate (link) | `<Link to="/path">` |
| Navigate (code) | `navigate('/path')` |
| URL params | `useParams()` |
| Query string | `useSearchParams()` |
| Nested layouts | `<Outlet />` in parent |
| Protected routes | Check auth, redirect to login |
| Code splitting | `lazy()` + `Suspense` |
